<tr>
<td bgcolor="#EEEEEE" colspan=2 class=news>
<table><tr><td valign=top><img src='images/icon_general.gif' alt='General News' border=0></td><td width="100%" valign=top><IMG SRC="http://www.buda.nildram.co.uk/max4.jpg" align=right> Over at <A HREF="http://www.machinima.com/articles/atf_max_payne/index.shtml" target=_new>Machinima</A> they've got an interview with Remedy Entertainment's Saku Lehtinen and Anssi Hyytiäinen, both level designers who were both involved in Max Paynes graphics, mainly the cinematics.<br><br><span class=quote>Overall, how pleased were you with how the cinematics turned out? <br><B>Anssi Hyytiäinen</B>: Overall, I'm pretty happy about them. There's always things that annoy me in there, and there's always room for improvement, but there's still some brilliant moments there that make me smile every time I see them. <br><B>Saku Lehtinen</B>: My feelings exactly. Compared to many other game cinematics (with the real-time engine) they are pretty good. I also get the most kick out of the ones which are good in both cinematic sense and which we were able to make economically by faking or hacking something crazy that was not supposed to be possible with the generic engine :-)</span><br><br>Read the interview <A HREF="http://www.machinima.com/articles/atf_max_payne/index.shtml" target=_new>here</A>.</td></tr></table>
</td>
